1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:07,349
Sometimes, you might not be able to

2

00:00:07,349  -->  00:00:10,890
run a true experiment to test your hypotheses due to not having

3

00:00:10,890  -->  00:00:15,280
multiple groups or not being able to control random assignment to groups.

4

00:00:15,279  -->  00:00:19,794
This will require you to consider alternative study designs.

5

00:00:19,795  -->  00:00:23,425
We can think of the types of study as lying on a spectrum

6

00:00:23,425  -->  00:00:27,664
based on the amount of control we have over the variables in play.

7

00:00:27,664  -->  00:00:30,094
On the end with a high level of control,

8

00:00:30,094  -->  00:00:32,195
we have an experiment.

9

00:00:32,195  -->  00:00:34,429
On the complete opposite side,

10

00:00:34,429  -->  00:00:38,634
where we have no control is the observational study.

11

00:00:38,634  -->  00:00:43,509
A classic example of this is on the risks posed by smoking.

12

00:00:43,509  -->  00:00:46,625
The hypothesis is that smoking tobacco

13

00:00:46,625  -->  00:00:50,869
increases the likelihood of developing diseases like lung cancer.

14

00:00:50,869  -->  00:00:54,799
Due to the risks of subjects actually developing a disease,

15

00:00:54,799  -->  00:00:58,729
it would be unreasonable not to mention unethical for us to

16

00:00:58,729  -->  00:01:03,509
make people smoke in order to run an experiment for testing our hypothesis.

17

00:01:03,509  -->  00:01:08,750
Instead, we need to rely on collecting data passively making connections

18

00:01:08,750  -->  00:01:14,840
between smoking rates and disease incidences based on groups or matched individuals.

19

00:01:14,840  -->  00:01:18,125
Establishing causality is very difficult

20

00:01:18,125  -->  00:01:21,700
or perhaps even impossible with an observational study,

21

00:01:21,700  -->  00:01:24,260
but if the feature of interest is something that

22

00:01:24,260  -->  00:01:27,375
the researcher cannot or should not manipulate,

23

00:01:27,375  -->  00:01:31,780
then an observational design might be the only path to take.

24

00:01:31,780  -->  00:01:35,000
You can also have studies that fall in the middle

25

00:01:35,000  -->  00:01:38,194
of observational studies and experiments.

26

00:01:38,194  -->  00:01:40,159
If your study applies some,

27

00:01:40,159  -->  00:01:43,625
but not all of the controls required of a true experiment,

28

00:01:43,625  -->  00:01:46,915
then you have a quasi-experiment instead.

29

00:01:46,915  -->  00:01:50,570
One example of this is when a video game company rolls out

30

00:01:50,569  -->  00:01:54,414
a patch to modify character and item attributes.

31

00:01:54,415  -->  00:01:59,035
This may then have an effect on character and item popularity.

32

00:01:59,034  -->  00:02:02,170
Since everyone is affected in the same way,

33

00:02:02,170  -->  00:02:04,445
this is a quasi-experiment.

34

00:02:04,444  -->  00:02:08,844
We only have one group to track and there&#39;s no control group.

35

00:02:08,844  -->  00:02:11,689
In our analysis, we can only compare

36

00:02:11,689  -->  00:02:16,354
the games ecosystem from before the patch and from after the patch.

37

00:02:16,354  -->  00:02:20,239
If we do see changes then there is the possibility for

38

00:02:20,240  -->  00:02:24,875
other factors to have caused these changes not just the patch itself.

39

00:02:24,875  -->  00:02:29,895
For this scenario, we wouldn&#39;t want to run the patch as a true experiment.

40

00:02:29,895  -->  00:02:34,500
If we randomly split users between pre-patch and post-patch groups,

41

00:02:34,500  -->  00:02:38,384
this fracturing could cause friction among the user base.

42

00:02:38,384  -->  00:02:43,094
Friends could end up in different versions and unable to play with one another.

43

00:02:43,094  -->  00:02:47,625
Even if we made a beta patch available for players to test out changes,

44

00:02:47,625  -->  00:02:50,120
this still wouldn&#39;t be a true experiment since

45

00:02:50,120  -->  00:02:53,585
the players would be self-selecting themselves into the test.

46

00:02:53,585  -->  00:02:56,450
It&#39;s quite possible that the players that will want to

47

00:02:56,449  -->  00:02:58,909
try out a new patch are different from the players in

48

00:02:58,909  -->  00:03:01,245
the general population limiting

49

00:03:01,245  -->  00:03:05,390
our ability to make conclusions about the effect of the patch.
